--- Failure <failure(-at-)nanbara.failsure.net> wrote:
> I've been driving and enjoying my '67 Westy less
> often since I moved
> downtown.  Mass transit is often easier, cheaper,
> and faster.  But I
> try to find excuses to drive the bus whenever I can.
> 
> Well, the bus has been making me scratch my head
> recently.  For a while
> I thought I must have forgotten how to set the
> valves, since I had 
> constant valve-sounding noise.  But every time I
> checked, they were fine.
> So I reasoned the noise was the warped pulley. 
> Replacing that with a less
> warped one (heh) didn't make it less.  So I bought a
> new one, and got a
> really straight generator pulley at a swap too. 
> Both pulleys are straight
> and true.  There's still noise, so I just figured it
> was valves and
> forgot about it.
> 
> Later on I was doing some work at Easterwood's
> place.  Running the engine
> I noticed that the noise seemed louder, and seemed
> to be coming from the
> center of the engine.  I verified with those present
> that this was not a
> normal sound for a VW engine to make.  We took it to
> Ron's place a couple
> days later since he had built the engine.  It
> appeared to be the fuel 
> pump making the noise, so I replaced both it and the
> pushrod one day at
> work...same noise.  
> 
> The noise is a clank-clank-clank that seems to come
> from the neighborhood
> of the crank pulley.  It's not super loud, and goes
> away more or less
> completely at any RPM much above fast idle, but it's
> quite pronounced at
> idle.  It seems to be louder when throttling down,
> and maybe a little louder
> when the engine is warm.  There's no slop in the
> crank pulley at all and
> it doesn't move in or out, up or down.  It's a 1600
> DP with the only mods
> being a full-flow case and a counter-balanced crank.
> 
> The next step seems to be pulling the engine and
> dropping it off at Ron's
> place...this is very difficult for me since I live
> in the city, and this
> is my only vehicle :-)  Can anybody think of
> anything else I might check
> before doing this?  It runs really great, but it
> makes that noise...
